---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SubNav from '../components/SubNav.astro';
import Champions from '../components/Champions.astro';
import Callout from '../components/Callout.astro';
import SourcesNote from '../components/SourcesNote.astro';

const subnavSections = [
  { id: 'climate-risk', label: 'Climate risk' },
  { id: 'nec-visibility', label: 'NEC visibility' },
  { id: 'federal-investment', label: 'Federal investment' },
  { id: 'fy27', label: 'FY27 deadline' },
  { id: 'mcbride-advocacy', label: "McBride's advocacy" },
  { id: 'champions', label: 'Champions' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="The Rail Corridor | Claymont to Fox Point"
  description="Climate risk, visibility on the busiest line in America, federal infrastructure investment, and what a freshman U.S. Representative can do for Amtrak funding."
  canonical="https://fox-point-riverwalk.vercel.app/rail-corridor/"
  ogImageAlt="The Northeast Corridor rail line passing the Fox Point shoreline along the Delaware River."
>
  <SubNav slot="subnav" sections={subnavSections} />

  <main id="main-content" tabindex="-1">
    <header class="panel page-intro">
      <p class="kicker">The Rail Corridor</p>
      <h1>Climate risk, ridership, and the federal investment passing Fox Point every few minutes.</h1>
      <p>Fox Point sits beside the busiest passenger rail line in America. Amtrak has documented the climate risk here, the federal investment passing through every few minutes, and the September 2026 deadline when key authorizations expire.</p>
    </header>

    <section class="panel" id="climate-risk">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Climate Risk On Our Stretch</p>
          <h2>Amtrak has documented the cost of doing nothing.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">Amtrak’s own climate planners have focused on the Wilmington stretch as the Northeast Corridor’s most exposed section — low elevation, two rivers, and a concentration of critical rail infrastructure at the river’s edge. Internal Amtrak modeling shows the Wilmington Maintenance Yard, West Yard Substation, Bellevue Substation, and the Consolidated National Operations Center all face significant flooding risk by 2050.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-big-row">
        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">$127M</p>
          <h3 class="risk-label">Losses already recorded</h3>
          <p class="risk-sub">Delay and revenue costs · 2006–2019</p>
          <div class="risk-bar-track">
            <div class="risk-bar-fill rfill-84"></div>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">450+</p>
          <h3 class="risk-label">Storm-related disruptions</h3>
          <p class="risk-sub">2006–2019 · Northeast Corridor</p>
          <div class="risk-bar-track">
            <div class="risk-bar-fill rfill-full"></div>
          </div>
        </article>
        <article class="risk-stat-card risk-hot-card">
          <p class="risk-number">$220M</p>
          <h3 class="risk-label">Possible future losses</h3>
          <p class="risk-sub">Next decade · if nothing changes</p>
          <div class="risk-gradient-bar"></div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="trio-grid">
        <article class="weather-card wc-rain">
          <p class="wc-title">Heavy storms are almost twice as common as they were in 1960.</p>
          <div class="wc-rows">
            <div class="wc-row">
              <span class="wc-year">1960s</span>
              <div class="dot-strip">
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-count">5×</span>
            </div>
            <div class="wc-row wc-row-now">
              <span class="wc-year">Today</span>
              <div class="dot-strip">
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span>
                <span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span><span aria-hidden="true" class="dot"></span>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-count">10×</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="wc-stat-num">+92%</p>
          <p class="wc-connect">→ More storms mean more chances for water to reach the tracks. Amtrak recorded more than 450 weather-related disruptions from 2006 to 2019.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="weather-card wc-intensity">
          <p class="wc-title">Flooding now comes from both stronger storms and rising water.</p>
          <div class="compound-scene" role="img" aria-label="Cross-section showing the Amtrak rail corridor squeezed between heavier storms above and rising seas below">
            <div class="cs-sky">
              <div class="cs-rain"></div>
              <span class="cs-badge cs-badge-top">↓ Storms: +55% more intense</span>
            </div>
            <div class="cs-track-zone">
              <div class="cs-rail"></div>
              <div class="cs-ties"></div>
              <div class="cs-rail"></div>
            </div>
            <div class="cs-flood-zone">
              <span class="cs-badge cs-badge-bot">↑ Sea level rising — Wilmington stretch identified by Amtrak</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="wc-connect">→ A restored living shoreline at Fox Point can help with both problems by slowing runoff and softening wave action before water reaches the rail edge.</p>
        </article>

        <article class="weather-card wc-heat">
          <p class="wc-title">Hotter summers will put more stress on the rail line.</p>
          <div class="wc-thermo-compare">
            <div class="wc-thermo-item">
              <div class="thermo-wrap">
                <div class="thermo"><div class="thermo-fill tf-now"></div></div>
                <div class="thermo-bulb tb-now"></div>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-year">Now</span>
            </div>
            <div class="wc-thermo-item">
              <div class="thermo-wrap">
                <div class="thermo"><div class="thermo-fill tf-2050"></div></div>
                <div class="thermo-bulb tb-2050"></div>
              </div>
              <span class="wc-year wc-year-now">2050</span>
            </div>
          </div>
          <p class="wc-stat-num">+4–5°F</p>
          <p class="wc-connect">→ Extreme heat can damage rails and signals. Restored wetland plants at Fox Point can help cool the corridor edge.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <SourcesNote sources={[
        { label: 'Amtrak Climate Vulnerability Assessment (2022)', href: '/docs/reference/amtrak-climate-vulnerability-assessment-summary-2022.pdf' },
        { label: "Bloomberg investigation of Amtrak's internal climate report", href: 'https://www.bloomberg.com/graphics/2018-amtrak-sea-level/' },
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section class="panel" id="nec-visibility">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Visibility On The Busiest Line In America</p>
          <h2>Trains pass Fox Point every few minutes.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">The Northeast Corridor serves more than 53 million Americans every year and connects a regional economy worth $5.9 trillion — about a fifth of the national total.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="risk-big-row">
        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">15M+</p>
          <h3 class="risk-label">FY25 ridership</h3>
          <p class="risk-sub">Acela + Northeast Regional · 21% above pre-pandemic</p>
        </article>
        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">628K</p>
          <h3 class="risk-label">Average weekday riders</h3>
          <p class="risk-sub">Amtrak + commuter railroads</p>
        </article>
        <article class="risk-stat-card">
          <p class="risk-number">$5.9T</p>
          <h3 class="risk-label">Regional GDP served</h3>
          <p class="risk-sub">~ 20% of national GDP</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <SourcesNote sources={[
        { label: 'Moulton–McBride bipartisan letter on Amtrak FY27 funding', href: 'https://moulton.house.gov/news/press-releases/moulton-mcbride-lead-bipartisan-group-colleagues-urging-full-funding-amtrak-and' },
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section class="panel" id="federal-investment">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Federal Infrastructure Investment</p>
          <h2>The 2021 Bipartisan Infrastructure Law put $66 billion into rail.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">That is the largest federal rail investment in Amtrak’s history. The numbers below are the verified IIJA figures — not the rounded approximations that sometimes circulate.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="corridor-brief-grid">
        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <h3 class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">Direct to Amtrak</h3>
          <p>$22 billion over five years.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <h3 class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">FRA Federal-State Partnership grants</h3>
          <p>$36 billion total, of which $24 billion is dedicated to the Northeast Corridor — bridges, tunnels, capital renewal, stations.</p>
        </article>
        <article class="corridor-brief-card">
          <h3 class="corridor-brief-eyebrow">Safety and grade crossings</h3>
          <p>$5 billion for CRISI safety grants; $3 billion for the Railroad Crossing Elimination Program.</p>
        </article>
      </div>

      <p class="section-copy">Specific Northeast Corridor projects announced under this funding include the Hudson Tunnel, the Frederick Douglass Tunnel, the Susquehanna River Bridge, and other capital-renewal work along the line.</p>

      <SourcesNote sources={[
        { label: 'Amtrak — New Era of Rail', href: 'https://www.amtrak.com/about-amtrak/new-era.html' },
        { label: 'FRA — IIJA programs', href: 'https://railroads.dot.gov/IIJA' },
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section class="panel" id="fy27">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">What’s At Stake In FY27</p>
          <h2>Key IIJA authorizations expire September 30, 2026.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">The Bipartisan Infrastructure Law is a five-year authorization. Without action by Congress, the authorized funding levels for Amtrak, the Federal-State Partnership grants that fund Northeast Corridor capital renewal, and the CRISI safety program revert at the end of FY26.</p>
      </div>

      <Callout label="The deadline">
        <p>Congresswoman Sarah McBride is co-leading bipartisan FY27 advocacy — including the March 2026 Moulton–McBride letter — pressing House leadership to keep the authorized funding levels in place for Amtrak, the Federal-State Partnership grants, and the rail-safety programs the Northeast Corridor depends on.</p>
      </Callout>

      <SourcesNote sources={[
        { label: 'Moulton–McBride FY27 letter', href: 'https://moulton.house.gov/news/press-releases/moulton-mcbride-lead-bipartisan-group-colleagues-urging-full-funding-amtrak-and' },
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section class="panel" id="mcbride-advocacy">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Sarah McBride's Federal Advocacy</p>
          <h2>What a freshman in the House minority can move.</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="section-copy">Congresswoman McBride is a first-term U.S. Representative in the House minority. Her practical power is advocacy and committee work — not direct appropriations. Below are the levers she has used on this corridor and this community.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="capital-stack">
        <article class="capital-row">
          <div class="capital-meta">
            <p class="capital-amount">Amtrak</p>
            <p class="capital-source">Federal advocacy</p>
          </div>
          <div class="capital-detail">
            <h3>Co-led the bipartisan FY27 Amtrak funding letter.</h3>
            <p>The March 2026 Moulton–McBride letter pressed House leadership for full FY27 Amtrak and Northeast Corridor rail funding. Co-leading a bipartisan letter is one of the few tools a freshman in the minority has to keep a deadline visible.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="capital-row">
          <div class="capital-meta">
            <p class="capital-amount">Formula</p>
            <p class="capital-source">Federal legislation</p>
          </div>
          <div class="capital-detail">
            <h3>Introduced the Highway Fair Share Act.</h3>
            <p>The bill aims to make federal highway formula funding more equitable across states. For Delaware — a small state whose formula share punches below the volume of traffic moving through it — that’s a structural fight, not a one-time ask.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="capital-row">
          <div class="capital-meta">
            <p class="capital-amount">District</p>
            <p class="capital-source">Local record</p>
          </div>
          <div class="capital-detail">
            <h3>Represented Claymont in the Delaware State Senate, 2021–2025.</h3>
            <p>District 1 covers Claymont, Bellefonte, Edgemoor, and parts of Wilmington — the exact community around Fox Point. That record is the ground for her standing on this corridor before she went to Congress.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <article class="capital-row">
          <div class="capital-meta">
            <p class="capital-amount">Naming</p>
            <p class="capital-source">State legislation</p>
          </div>
          <div class="capital-detail">
            <h3>Co-sponsored the McDowell naming for the Claymont Transit Center.</h3>
            <p>As a state senator, she co-sponsored the legislation naming the Claymont Transportation Center the Harris B. McDowell III Transportation Center — recognizing the senator whose record built the community Fox Point sits inside.</p>
          </div>
        </article>
      </div>

      <SourcesNote sources={[
        { label: 'mcbride.house.gov', href: 'https://mcbride.house.gov/' },
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section class="panel read-next" aria-label="Read next">
      <p class="section-label">Read Next</p>
      <div class="read-next-grid">
        <a class="read-next-card" href="/ecological-restoration/">
          <p class="read-next-eyebrow">Ecological Restoration</p>
          <h3>The federal water rule and the endangered sturgeon on this stretch.</h3>
          <span class="read-next-cta">Read →</span>
        </a>
        <a class="read-next-card" href="/what-this-means-for-delaware/">
          <p class="read-next-eyebrow">What This Means for Delaware</p>
          <h3>The transit gateway and trail network this corridor connects to.</h3>
          <span class="read-next-cta">Read →</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="panel" id="champions">
      <div class="section-header">
        <div>
          <p class="section-label">Champions</p>
          <h2>The people whose record and position make this work possible.</h2>
        </div>
      </div>
      <Champions ids={['mcdowell', 'mcbride', 'cruce']} />
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
